  "prompt": "What are the comparative legal approaches to money laundering across different nations?",
  "response": "Money laundering legal approaches vary significantly across different nations, with key variations in:\n\n1. Regulatory Framework\n- United States: Comprehensive Bank Secrecy Act and Anti-Money Laundering (AML) regulations\n- European Union: Directive (EU) 2015/849 establishing uniform standards\n- United Kingdom: Sophisticated legal infrastructure with Proceeds of Crime Act\n- Developing countries: Often less robust regulatory environments\n\n2. Criminalization Scope\n- Some nations criminalize money laundering as a standalone offense\n- Others treat it as derivative of predicate criminal activities\n- Varying definitions of what constitutes money laundering\n\n3. Reporting Requirements\n- Different thresholds for suspicious transaction reporting\n- Varying levels of financial institution compliance obligations\n- Differences in customer due diligence standards\n\n4. Enforcement Mechanisms\n- Varying penalties ranging from financial sanctions to imprisonment\n- Different investigative powers for law enforcement\n- Divergent approaches to asset seizure and confiscation\n\n5. International Cooperation\n- Participation in global frameworks like FATF recommendations\n- Bilateral and multilateral information sharing agreements\n- Extradition protocols for money laundering offenses\n\nComparative analysis reveals significant complexity and ongoing international legal evolution.",
